Before llama is installed,it is very important to check the RAM.
In my case, I ran into an error which read something like below;

"Loading model... /ggml_aligned_malloc: insufficient memory (attempted to allocate 14336.00 MB)
ggml_backend_cpu_buffer_type_alloc_buffer: failed to allocate buffer of size 15032385536
alloc_tensor_range: failed to allocate CPU buffer of size 15032385536
llama_init_from_model: failed to initialize the context: failed to allocate buffer for kv cache
common_init_result: failed to create context with model '/home/ashamraze/llama.cpp/models/llama-3.2-3b-instruct-q4_k_m.gguf'
common_init_from_params: failed to create context with model '/home/ashamraze/llama.cpp/models/llama-3.2-3b-instruct-q4_k_m.gguf'
Segmentation fault (core dumped)"

So llama.cpp loaded the GGUF, then tried to allocate ~15 GB for context/KV cache and blew up. One possible explanation could be running with a large context (often the default in some configs/scripts), e.g. --ctx 8192 or higher. KV cache memory grows roughly with:

context length (ctx), model size (3B), and/or data type for KV (f16 vs q8_0, etc.)

I did not try to quantize the cache and therefore debug it since I was running out of time, however running it on a device which has available RAM allowed me to build it successfully.

Second important step is to understand CPU cores usage during any task before running llama on top of it. This step is crucial because it gives you a baseline
of what you are dealing with in terms of compute before running llama, and once you run llama you can compare cpu usage with that.

For that, I ran 'lscpu' and checked the clock frequencies of cpu before running llama. Then, I ran llama in the background and used 'htop' or 'top' to 
look at tall the cores that are busy during the llama run.
I found that my linux machine was using all 8 cores. Note that this one did not have any classification of master/slave or big/small cores. 

Another useful thing is to bind your tasks to the numbers of cores and observe how it affects performance. The metric of perfofrmance is tokens/second.
 The goal here is to observe the 't/s' for both prompt processing and token generation. I specified that in command such as '-p 512' and '-n 128'.
for t in 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8; do
    echo "=== t = $t ==="
    ./llama-bench -m "$MODEL" -t $t -p 128 -n 256 -r 5
done
